# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: indian-ocean-trade
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:indian-ocean-trade/2005-in-africa-p01] Kofi Annan, secretary general of the UN has sought to strengthen the partnership between the UN and the African Union for Africa to reach the Millennium Development Goals by 2015.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/2005-in-africa-p01] He declared that "Africa isn't on schedule to reach the Millennium Development Goals.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/2005-in-africa-p01] But it will be able to reach these goals if the world partnership, promised a long time ago, does come together completely".
[src:indian-ocean-trade/2005-in-africa-p01] The question of how to represent Africa in the best possible way in the UN Security Council was delayed, following a disagreement among the member countries of the African Union.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/2005-in-africa-p01] This was referred to a committee composed of 15 countries to assemble in Swaziland from February 2005.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/2005-in-africa-p01] The mandate of the current chairman, Olusegun Obasanjo, president of Nigeria, was prolonged from July 2005 to January 2006.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/2005-in-africa-p01] Next summits will be held in Libya in July 2005 and in Sudan in January 2006.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/2005-in-africa-p01] The summit also touched the situation in Togo and welcomed a delegation, led by Kokou Tozoun, minister of foreign affairs.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/2005-in-africa-p01] A statement was made, inviting "the international community to encourage the Togo authorities to do its utmost to establish a swift and peaceful return of the peace process in the country".
[src:indian-ocean-trade/2005-in-africa-p01] Omar Bongo Ondimba, present chairman of the Cemac, yielded his chair to Teodoro Obiang Nguema, president of Equatorial Guinea.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/2005-in-africa-p01] Tandja Mamadou, president of Niger returned to the chair of the UEMOA following the summit of the organisation in Niamey (Niger) on 30 March 2005.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/2005-in-africa-p01] Different heads of state participated in the summit: Abdoulaye Wade (Senegal), Mathieu Kérékou (Benin), Blaise Compaoré (Burkina Faso), Amadou Toumani Touré (Mali), Henrique Rosa (Guinea-Bissau) and Tandja Mamadou (Niger).
[src:indian-ocean-trade/2005-in-africa-p01] Togo was represented by Koffi Sama, prime minister, and Côte d'Ivoire by Théodore Mel Eg, minister for regional integration and the African Union.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/2005-in-africa-p01] In a final communiqué, the UEMOA congratulated itself for "the results on price stability in the Union, following a better provisioning of the food markets" and "welcomed the actions intended to preserve the value of the common currency", the CFA franc.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/2005-in-africa-p01] During a 6-year period, this agreement envisages broad autonomy for the south of Sudan which will have its own government and an autonomous army.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/2005-in-africa-p01] At the end of this period, a self-determination referendum will be organized.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/2005-in-africa-p01] The income resulting from oil will be shared in equal share between the south and north.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/2005-in-africa-p01] In addition, the government will have 70% of the positions in the central administration against 30% for the southern rebels.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/2005-in-africa-p01] Lastly, the Sharia (Islamic law) will be into force only in the north of the country, with Muslim majority.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/2005-in-africa-p01] It will not be applied in the south, having a Christian and animist majority.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/2005-in-africa-p01] On 10 January, thousands of Sudanese expressed their joy in the streets of Khartoum.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/2005-in-africa-p01] The National Liberation Council of the Sudan People's Liberation Movement (SPLM) ratified unanimously on 24 January the peace agreement in Rumbek.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/2005-in-africa-p01] On 5 February 2005, president Gnassingbé Eyadéma died after having led Togo for 38 years.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/2005-in-africa-p01] According to the constitution, the chairman of the National Assembly should have been acting president until new presidential elections, to be held in 60 days.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/2005-in-africa-p01] The army however decided to bring to power a son of the late president, Faure Gnassingbé Eyadéma.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/2005-in-africa-p01] To endorse the decision of the army, the parliament urgently modified the constitution.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/2005-in-africa-p01] The African Union, the ECOWAS, the UN, the European Union condemned what they called a "coup d'etat" and demanded the re-establishment of the constitutional order.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/2005-in-africa-p01] In spite of a ban on public demonstrations issued by the government, the principal opposition parties demanded free and pluralist elections and appealed each day for peaceful demonstrations, which gathered several hundreds to a few thousand people.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/2005-in-africa-p01] These were dispersed by the police, using teargas.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/2005-in-africa-p01] On 25 February Faure Gnassingbé Eyadéma renounced from the position of president of the Republic, and announced to be standing as a candidate to the presidential elections, to be held on 24 April 2005.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/2005-in-africa-p01] Abass Bonfoh, vice-president of the National Assembly became acting president.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/2005-in-africa-p01] The campaign was held in a climate of violence.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/2005-in-africa-p01] The opposition denounced the conditions in which they had to prepare, and request a postponement of the election.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/2005-in-africa-p01] Two days before the poll, François Boko, Minister for the Interior of the temporary government, requested the postponement of the scrutiny.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/2005-in-africa-p01] In a press conference, he denounced "a suicidal electoral process".
[src:indian-ocean-trade/2005-in-africa-p01] It is marked by much violence, resulting in dozens of deaths.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/2005-in-africa-p01] The results were proclaimed on 26 April: Faure Gnassingbé, wins the election with 60.22% of the votes, before Emmanuel Bob Akitani with 38.19% and Harry Olympio with 0.55%.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/2005-in-africa-p01] After the announcement, there was an outbreak of demonstrations in several cities of the country, denouncing the massive fraud.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/2005-in-africa-p01] Clashes between demonstrators and the police occurred, involving hundreds of victims, died or wounded.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/2005-in-africa-p01] Thousands of Togolese took refuge in Benin.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/2005-in-africa-p01] ECOWAS, the European Union and France recognized the victory of Faure Gnassingbé Eyadema and called for the installation of a government of national unity.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/2005-in-africa-p01] This was rejected by the radical opposition, that requested the cancellation of the elections because of the massive fraud.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/2005-in-africa-p01] On 8 June, Edem Kodjo, president of the *Convergence patriotique panafricaine* (CPP, moderate opposition), is appointed Prime Minister.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/2006-in-africa] was barred from entering due to the age limit.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/2006-in-africa] In the second round, Boni won the presidency with a majority of 74.29% against Houndbédji.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/2006-in-africa] won 64.67% of the vote, thus retaining his presidency.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/2006-in-africa] On November 15, the Independent Electoral Commission (CEI) announced that Kabila had won the vote with 58.05%, while Bemba had received only 41.95% support, and declared Kabila president.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/2006-in-africa] upheld the election result, stating that Kabila was the winner by "absolute majority".
[src:indian-ocean-trade/2006-in-africa] Throughout the year, rioting and violence was rampant in many parts of the country.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/2006-in-africa] Out of the total 120 seats, coalition parties had won a total of 99 seats, compared to the 17 won by the 6 parties of the opposition.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/2006-in-africa] The remaining 4 seats were won by independents.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/2006-in-africa] No major incidents related to the election were reported.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/2006-in-africa] was voted in for a second term in office with 54.80%, prevailing over 13 other candidates.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/2006-in-africa] Confusion over preliminary results led opposition candidates to question the validity of the elections, and official complaints were filed to the constitutional court.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/2006-in-africa] On December 23, the court ruled that Ravalomanana had indeed won the election.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/2006-in-africa] Furthermore, some candidates were barred from participating for various reasons.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/2006-in-africa] The elections were considered to be free and transparent by all observers and political parties.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/2006-in-africa] narrowly voted to uphold the election result, despite many mentions of irregularities.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/2006-in-africa] However, a multitude of charges were brought against Besigye in the months leading up to the election, sparking claims of fabrication and widespread protests by Besigye supporters.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/2006-in-africa] President of Sudan Omar al-Bashir refuses the deployment of 20,000 *Blue Helmets* in a United Nations peacekeeping force in Darfur in accordance with United Nations Security Council Resolution 1706 adopted on September 1.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/abortion-in-africa] In Africa, abortion is subject to various national abortion laws.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/abortion-in-africa] Most women in Africa live in countries with restrictive laws.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/abortion-in-africa] Most countries in Africa are parties to the African Union's Maputo Protocol, the only international treaty that defines a right to abortion.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/abortion-in-africa] Sub-Saharan Africa is the world region with the highest rates of unsafe abortions and abortion mortality.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/abortion-in-africa] Most abortions in the region are unsafe.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/abortion-in-africa] The region has the highest rate of unintended pregnancy, the primary motive for abortion.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/abortion-in-africa] The most likely women to have abortions are young, unmarried, or urban.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/abortion-in-africa] Abortion-rights movements emphasize public health arguments about the maternal mortality rate.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/abortion-in-africa] Anti-abortion movements argue that the practice of abortion was imposed upon Africa by foreign powers.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/abortion-in-africa] Many women keep abortions secret due to stigma.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/abortion-in-africa] Medical abortion using misoprostol is available from health providers and pharmacies, and is usually safe.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/abortion-in-africa] Surgical abortion is regulated by national guidelines in countries with legal abortion.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/abortion-in-africa] Abortion has existed in Africa since ancient times.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/abortion-in-africa] Many bans on abortions were implemented during the colonial era.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/abortion-in-africa] Since then, reproductive health laws, constitutional amendments, and judicial decisions have been passed to permit abortion under varying grounds.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/abortion-in-africa] International treaties have influenced reform.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/abortion-in-africa] United States policy has influenced the abortion debate.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/abortion-in-africa] Constitutions, judicial decisions, health codes, and laws may mention abortion.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/abortion-in-africa] Many countries' reproductive health laws specify legal grounds for abortion, often following the terms of international laws.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/abortion-in-africa] Guidelines and codes of medical ethics may describe implementation of the law or may be contradicted by the law.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/abortion-in-africa] Most African countries where abortion is legal do not implement them in a way that makes abortion broadly available.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/abortion-in-africa] Abortion is unconditionally legal in Benin, Guinea-Bissau, Cape Verde, São Tomé and Príncipe, South Africa, and Tunisia.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/abortion-in-africa] Zambia allows abortion for any health or socioeconomic reason.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/abortion-in-africa] As of 2019, 45% of women of reproductive age in Sub-Saharan Africa live in countries with highly restrictive laws, 47% are under moderately restrictive laws, and 8% in countries where abortion is broadly legal.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/abortion-in-africa] Some countries with restrictive laws apply them inclusively.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/abortion-in-africa] Ethiopia uses a broad interpretation of its law.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/abortion-in-africa] Ghana states that no evidence is needed to prove grounds for legal abortion.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/abortion-in-africa] In countries where abortion is conditionally legal, abortion is not accessible in practice due to complicated legal processes.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/abortion-in-africa] Many women think abortion is illegal, regardless of whether it is.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/abortion-in-africa] Those who think abortion is illegal are more likely to undergo unsafe treatments, fearing legal issues of seeking professional care.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/abortion-in-africa] In Ghana, Zambia, and Kenya, most women do not know the laws legalising abortion.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/abortion-in-africa] Medical providers may be uncomfortable providing abortions out of fear of anti-abortion backlash.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/abortion-in-africa] In some countries, unclear laws deter them from providing abortion.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/abortion-in-africa] The African Union's Maputo Protocol secures the right to abortion in the cases of rape, incest, or threat to the life or health of the pregnant woman.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/abortion-in-africa] As of 2022, 42 out of 55 countries in Africa have signed it.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/abortion-in-africa] Most countries in Africa have ratified the United Nations Convention on the Rights of the Child and African Charter on the Rights and Welfare of the Child, which provide a right to sexual and reproductive healthcare for minors.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/abortion-in-africa] The Southern African Development Community has written policy frameworks to decriminalise abortion.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/abortion-in-africa] Article 5 of its SADC Sexual and Reproductive Health Rights Strategy (2019–2030) aims to reduce unsafe abortion and teenage pregnancy rates.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/abortion-in-africa] From Ancient Egypt until the 15th century, women would consult a pharmacopoeia about herbs that worked as contraceptives or abortifacients.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/abortion-in-africa] Abortion was practiced by over 400 cultures in pre-colonial Africa.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/abortion-in-africa] The Malagasy people used it to limit the sizes of families.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/abortion-in-africa] The Maasai people used it when women were impregnated by men who could not provide for the child.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/abortion-in-africa] The Maasai and the Owambo people used it in cases of teenage pregnancy.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/abortion-in-africa] The Efik people used it if they predicted birth defects.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/abortion-in-africa] In South Africa, Cape Malays used red geraniums, Khoekhoe people used thorn bushes, and Zulu people used a shrub called *uhlungughlungu*.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/abortion-in-africa] Laws banning abortion are inherited from colonial powers.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/abortion-in-africa] All of the countries that colonised Africa have since decriminalised abortion.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/abortion-in-africa] Colonial abortion laws were based on laws developed by European governments in the 18th century—civil law of France, Belgium, and Portugal, common law of England, and, in the case of South Africa's law, the Roman-Dutch law system.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/abortion-in-africa] Laws were influenced by Christian and Islamic law.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/abortion-in-africa] Islamic societies often practiced abortion.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/abortion-in-africa] Islamic schools had differing opinions of it.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/abortion-in-africa] In 1985, Ghana legalised abortion under certain grounds.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/abortion-in-africa] It reviewed the law in 2003 to develop a plan for implementation.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/abortion-in-africa] In the 1990s, nearly three-quarters of emergency gynecological admissions in Africa were due to unsafe abortion.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/abortion-in-africa] The rate of abortions resulting in hospitalisation was over two-thirds in Egypt and nearly one-quarter in Nigeria.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/abortion-in-africa] Parties to the 1994 International Conference on Population and Development pledged to increase access to family planning services, safe and legal abortion, and post-abortion care, which influenced reforms in Africa.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/abortion-in-africa] Before the conference, African governments had avoided the stigmatised topic of unsafe abortion.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/abortion-in-africa] In the late 1990s and early 2000s, post-abortion care (PAC) services were introduced in Egypt, Ethiopia, Ghana, Kenya, Malawi, Nigeria, Senegal, South Africa, Tanzania, Uganda, Zambia, and Zimbabwe.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/abortion-in-africa] Ipas led the Woman-Centred Abortion Care program, which addressed the use of MVA and the availability of providers.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/abortion-in-africa] South Africa decriminalised abortion in 1996 through a political coalition.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/abortion-in-africa] The African National Congress noted that unsafe abortion had a disproportionate impact on Black South Africans.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/abortion-in-africa] Between 1996 and 2003, Burkina Faso, Mali, Guinea, Niger, Chad, and Benin revised their strict abortion bans from the Napoleonic Code to allow abortion in the cases of rape, incest, and fetal impairment.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/abortion-in-africa] In 2004, lawmakers debated abortion in Kenya.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/abortion-in-africa] Senegal and Madagascar are the only Sub-Saharan countries that have passed reproductive health laws without specifying legal grounds for abortion, as of 2020.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/abortion-in-africa] The African Union's 2003 Maputo Protocol is the only human rights treaty that provides criteria for abortion.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/abortion-in-africa] The Maputo Plan of Action calls to "compile and disseminate data on the magnitude and consequences of unsafe abortion." Since the Maputo Protocol, 21 African countries have expanded their legal grounds for abortion.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/abortion-in-africa] As of 2023, 44 member states have ratified the it, 8 have signed but not ratified it, and 3 have not signed it.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/abortion-in-africa] Of those that have ratified it, 12 exceed its provisions, 11 fully comply with the provisions, 16 partially comply, and 4 do not comply.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/abortion-in-africa] Few countries in North Africa signed the protocol until the 2010s.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/abortion-in-africa] Some legal scholars have criticized the Maputo Protocol for listing specific grounds to allow abortion.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/abortion-in-africa] Others have argued that the continent's human rights guidelines provide for the complete legalisation of abortion.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/abortion-in-africa] In the Democratic Republic of the Congo, Article 14 was enacted after a 2018 ruling by the Constitutional Court invoked an article saying national treaties take precedence over national law.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/abortion-in-africa] It was the first country in Francophone Africa to expand legal abortion.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/abortion-in-africa] In 2019, Rwanda, which had removed its reservation to the Maputo Protocol in 2012, implemented the WHO's definition of health, which provides for the terms of Article 14.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/abortion-in-africa] Abortion laws were liberalised in Ethiopia in 2006 and Ghana in 2006 and 2012.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/abortion-in-africa] In 2008, the ACHPR decided in *Institute for Human Rights and Development in Africa v.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/abortion-in-africa] Angola* that the ban on cruel punishment extends to "lack of access to medicine or medical care." The following year, Nigeria became the first country in the world to include misoprostol for PAC in its essential medicines list.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/abortion-in-africa] In the Gambia, the Women's Act 2010 provides for safe abortion if there is a risk to the life of the mother or fetus.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/abortion-in-africa] Kenya's 2010 constitution, passed by a referendum, permits abortion if there is risk to life or health.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/abortion-in-africa] In 2012, São Tomé and Príncipe changed its penal code from completely banning abortion to allowing it without restriction, and Somalia authorised abortion in emergencies in its new constitution.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/abortion-in-africa] The same year, Mauritius reformed its law, influenced by a Mauritian member of the Convention on the Elimination of All Forms of Discrimination against Women.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/abortion-in-africa] Planned Parenthood created legal networks to advocate for safe abortion in East Africa.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/abortion-in-africa] The program began in 2011; in the following decade, it trained 75 lawyers and brought seven cases to court, all of which succeeded.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/abortion-in-africa] The International Federation of Gynaecology and Obstetrics's Advocacy for Safe Abortion project, launched in 2019, has partnered with OB/GYN societies of African countries.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/abortion-in-africa] The MAMA network has worked to expand access to self-managed abortion.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/abortion-in-africa] Malawi proposed the Termination of Pregnancy Bill in July 2015, but legislators have not yet debated it, as of 2020.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/abortion-in-africa] Sierra Leone's Safe Abortion Act was passed by its parliament in 2015 and 2016, but the president refused to sign it.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/abortion-in-africa] In a 2015 joint statement, the United Nations, the Inter-American Commission on Human Rights, and the ACHPR said that criminalizing abortion is a form of gender discrimination.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/abortion-in-africa] The ACHPR began a campaign for African governments to decriminalize abortion in 2016 and reiterated this goal in 2021.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/abortion-in-africa] The COVID-19 pandemic led to disruption in the supply chains of medical abortion and contraceptives.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/abortion-in-africa] DKT International, a major provider of such products, ran low on its stock after manufacturing disruptions in Asia.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/abortion-in-africa] MSI Reproductive Choices suspended its programs in Kenya and Uganda.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/abortion-in-africa] Health workers predicted a rise in unsafe abortion cases.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/abortion-in-africa] Several Presidents of the United States have instated the Mexico City policy, which bans federal funding for NGOs operating abroad from performing or advocating for abortion as family planning.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/abortion-in-africa] It was introduced in 1984 by the administration of Ronald Reagan.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/abortion-in-africa] Since then, Democratic presidents have rescinded the policy and Republican presidents have reinstated it.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/abortion-in-africa] Organisations such as Planned Parenthood and Marie Stopes International have chosen to lose federal funding when it is in effect.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/abortion-in-africa] The instatement of the policy by George W.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/abortion-in-africa] Bush was strongly correlated with higher abortion rates in Sub-Saharan African countries affected by it.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/abortion-in-africa] Countries that had lost more aid funding had higher pregnancy rates and lower contraceptive use than those less affected.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/abortion-in-africa] The United States overturned its right to abortion in the 2022 case *Dobbs v.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/abortion-in-africa] Jackson Women's Health Organization*, which impacted the abortion debate in Africa.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/abortion-in-africa] Abortion providers faced an increase in threats.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/abortion-in-africa] American groups provided funding for anti-abortion activists.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/abortion-in-africa] Anti-abortion groups in Kenya challenged the country's recent ruling that abortion is a constitutional right, which had cited Roe v.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/abortion-in-africa] The governor of Lagos State, Nigeria, suspended guidelines for therapeutic abortion.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/abortion-in-africa] Ethiopian groups such as the U.S.-based Family Watch International challenged its law legalizing abortion, and protestors gathered in Hawassa and Addis Ababa.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/abortion-in-africa] Family Watch International held a meeting at Uganda's presidential office with delegates from 20 African countries.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/abortion-in-africa] Its leader said in a speech in Malawi that it was combatting a "sexual social recolonization of Africa".
[src:indian-ocean-trade/abortion-in-africa] Days after the ruling, Sierra Leone's president Julius Maada Bio announced his plan to protect abortion.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/abortion-in-africa] Benin implemented one of Africa's most permissive abortion laws.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/abortion-in-africa] In 2023, Republican members of the United States House of Representatives defunded PEPFAR, a foreign aid plan that lowered rates of HIV/AIDS in Africa.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/abortion-in-africa] It had previously had bipartisan support despite concerns about abortion.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/abortion-in-africa] African aid recipients who lost funding included many abortion opponents.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/abortion-in-africa] In September, 350 African religious leaders wrote that PEPFAR should be re-implemented and denied that it led to abortions.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/abortion-in-africa] According to reporting by the Center for Countering Digital Hate and MSI Reproductive Choices in March 2024, Meta and Google restricted abortion information in Africa, Latin America and Asia.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/abortion-in-africa] MSI said that Google flagged the term "pregnancy options" and Facebook deleted its advertisements while allowing advertisements including misinformation related to abortion.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/abortion-in-africa] Meta said it would review the claims and Google said it did not restrict the subject.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/abortion-in-africa] Online barriers to information contributed to women in Africa not knowing about the legality of abortion.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/abortion-in-africa] As of 2010–2014, Africa has an annual average of 8.2 million abortions, a rate of 34 per 1,000 women of reproductive age equating to a total of 41 million.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/abortion-in-africa] The rate varies from 31 per 1,000 in Western Africa to 34 per 1,000 in Northern Africa.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/abortion-in-africa] The ratio of pregnancies resulting in abortion is 15%.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/abortion-in-africa] This percentage varies from 12% in Western Africa to 24% in Southern Africa.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/abortion-in-africa] The abortion rate is the same in places where abortion is or is not permitted.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/abortion-in-africa] Sub-Saharan Africa is the region with the most unsafe abortions.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/abortion-in-africa] As of 2024, 77% of abortions are unsafe and nearly half are least safe, as classified by the World Health Organization (WHO).
[src:indian-ocean-trade/abortion-in-africa] Doctors Without Borders estimated in 2023 that abortions in hospitals in poor or conflict-affected places are five to seven times more likely to lead to serious complications.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/abortion-in-africa] As of 2014, 9% of maternal deaths in Africa (16,000 deaths) were caused by abortions.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/abortion-in-africa] Sub-Saharan Africa has the highest rate of abortions resulting in deaths, at 185 per 100,000, as of 2019.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/abortion-in-africa] The highest fatality rate is in Middle Africa and the lowest is in Southern Africa, where most abortions are legal.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/abortion-in-africa] The most commonly treated complication of abortion is haemorrhage.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/abortion-in-africa] About 10% of women treated for abortion complications have infections.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/abortion-in-africa] The abortion mortality rate is higher among women who have infections.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/abortion-in-africa] Unintended pregnancies cause the overwhelming majority of abortions.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/abortion-in-africa] Sub-Saharan Africa has the world's highest unintended pregnancy rate.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/abortion-in-africa] As of 2017, the continent's unintended pregnancy rate is 89 per 1,000 women of reproductive age.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/abortion-in-africa] Of the 21.6 million unintended pregnancies annually, 38% result in abortion.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/abortion-in-africa] About 58 million women have an unmet need for contraception.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/abortion-in-africa] As of 2019, the rate of use of modern contraceptives is 29% among married women, which has tripled since 1990.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/abortion-in-africa] Though Sub-Saharan Africa has the highest average desired fertility, the desire for large families is declining.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/abortion-in-africa] Sexually active unmarried women have higher-than-average rates of modern contraceptive use than married women, but are more likely to not want to be pregnant, so they have more unmet need for contraception.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/abortion-in-africa] Demographics of women who are more likely to receive abortions are those who are young, are unmarried, are in school, do not have children, live in cities, are better educated, and are wealthier.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/abortion-in-africa] Reasons for seeking abortions include wanting to delay being a mother, being unmarried, family honor, financial pressure, and wanting to continue education.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/abortion-in-africa] Women who have experienced intimate partner violence are more likely to have abortions.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/abortion-in-africa] The abortion rate is 26 per 1,000 for married women and 36 per 1,000 for unmarried women.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/abortion-in-africa] Premarital pregnancy is stigmatised, so unmarried women often want to terminate their pregnancies.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/abortion-in-africa] Sexually active adolescents have much higher rates of abortion than the average.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/abortion-in-africa] Unmet need for contraception causes 86% of unintended pregnancies among Sub-Saharan adolescents.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/abortion-in-africa] Some adolescents cannot afford birth control or fear stigma from providers.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/abortion-in-africa] Adolescents have higher rates of abortion in all African regions.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/abortion-in-africa] Adolescents, especially students, have knowledge of abortion services but do not use them due to the cost and stigma.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/abortion-in-africa] Though international treaties guarantee the medical autonomy of minors, many African countries' laws do not guarantee access to abortion for minors.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/abortion-in-africa] Abortion rates are higher in cities, where services and providers are concentrated.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/abortion-in-africa] Urban women have lower rates of unintended pregnancy, due to higher contraceptive use; however, they are more likely to want fewer children or to have higher agency.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/abortion-in-africa] Sub-Saharan Africa has few trained medical professionals, especially in rural areas, where 60% of the population lives.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/abortion-in-africa] Laws requiring abortion to be authorised by medical professionals are difficult to adhere to.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/abortion-in-africa] The option for conscientious objection limits the number of doctors who can perform abortions.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/abortion-in-africa] Male partners of women who have abortions may be involved through financial or emotional support.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/abortion-in-africa] Some men avoid involvement due to denial of responsibility or suspicion of promiscuity, and some women do not tell their partners as they fear lack of support.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/abortion-in-africa] Those who are involved may decide the method of abortion.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/abortion-in-africa] Feminist activists advocate for more permissive abortion laws.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/abortion-in-africa] Public health frameworks, emphasising the rates of morbidity and mortality from unsafe abortion, are effective.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/abortion-in-africa] These frameworks often do not address psychological effects of unsafe abortion.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/abortion-in-africa] The "pro-choice" argument is popular in the Western world, but less effective in Africa.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/abortion-in-africa] African feminists criticise this stance for focusing on choice regarding abortion rather than other factors of women's sexual and reproductive experiences.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/abortion-in-africa] The framework of reproductive justice has been proposed to be relevant to African experiences.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/abortion-in-africa] International organisations such as the Center for Reproductive Rights work to establish safe, legal abortion in Africa.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/abortion-in-africa] A 2024 survey found that over half of people in South Africa and about 90% in Kenya and Nigeria oppose legal abortion.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/abortion-in-africa] People in rural South Africa view abortion as a form of killing that violated traditional values.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/abortion-in-africa] Men in Kenya view abortion as a way for women to hide culturally deviant behavior.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/abortion-in-africa] A decolonisation framework is common, which argues that abortion has been imposed on Africa by colonial powers.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/abortion-in-africa] The argument is based on the fact that American organisations lead advocacy efforts for legal abortion in Africa.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/abortion-in-africa] Postcolonial theorists have criticised this philosophy for presenting a homogenous view of African culture.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/abortion-in-africa] Little data exists on methods of abortion.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/abortion-in-africa] Some abortion patients do not know what methods they use.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/abortion-in-africa] Lack of knowledge causes women to obtain unsafe abortions or face delays that limit their options.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/abortion-in-africa] Women who are older, less educated, in rural areas, or do not know health workers are less likely to have adequate knowledge of abortion.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/abortion-in-africa] Social networks influence women's decisions about abortion.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/abortion-in-africa] Many women make multiple attempts at abortions, as they seek out professional services after inexpensive methods often fail.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/abortion-in-africa] This delays the final procedure, which leads to higher risk.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/abortion-in-africa] They may opt for folk remedies over formal services.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/abortion-in-africa] Women and girls in rural areas are more likely to more likely to use traditional methods.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/abortion-in-africa] Abortions outside of the formal health system are more likely to cause complications.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/abortion-in-africa] Though women wish for safe abortions, fears of legal and social repercussions may lead to more unsafe abortions.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/abortion-in-africa] Some women who know about safe methods cannot afford them.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/abortion-in-africa] Countries with legal abortion have implemented guidelines from international medical standards and offer abortions in public facilities.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/abortion-in-africa] Post-abortion care is always legal and obligated by medical ethics.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/abortion-in-africa] Abortion providers use coded language in their advertising to avoid objections.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/abortion-in-africa] Religious NGOs are a major source of abortion care but are more likely to choose conscientious objection.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/abortion-in-africa] Many surgical abortions use dilation and curettage, a method that is not recommended by the WHO.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/abortion-in-africa] Legal restrictions and social stigma lead to women getting clandestine abortions or self-induced abortions.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/abortion-in-africa] Methods of ineffective abortions include ingesting herbal remedies, caustics, or store-bought products falsely believed to induce abortions; using over-the-counter drugs in large quantities; or inserting cassava sticks, metal objects, or branches into the vagina.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/abortion-in-africa] Safe self-managed abortion is considered a possible safe option by the WHO.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/abortion-in-africa] In Africa, people who receive or provide self-managed abortions may face prosecution or stigma.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/abortion-in-africa] The widespread use of misoprostol for medical abortions has made abortions safer.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/abortion-in-africa] It has been available in the region since 2005, when the WHO added it to its list of its list of essential medicines, off of which many African countries base their guidelines.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/abortion-in-africa] The WHO recommends a procedure of mifepristone followed by misoprostol, or use of only the latter if the former is unavailable.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/abortion-in-africa] Mifepristone is more expensive and has fewer uses than misoprostol, so it is not widely available.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/abortion-in-africa] Many women purchase misoprostol without prescriptions.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/abortion-in-africa] Pharmacies are a preferred source for healthcare as they are accessible and affordable.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/abortion-in-africa] Some providers clandestinely offer misoprostol pills which may be expired or adulterated or not contain enough of the active ingredient to be effective.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/abortion-in-africa] Many women lack information about how to use misoprostol.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/abortion-in-africa] Knowledge of mifepristone and misoprostol is higher in younger women.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/abortion-in-africa] Providers and clients in several countries widely approve of medical abortion as it can be done privately, is more accessible and affordable than other methods, and is considered safe and painless.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/abortion-in-africa] Access to medical abortion may lessen the stigma of abortion.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/abortion-in-africa] Implementing misoprostol at lower-level health centers has been shown to be effective.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/abortion-in-africa] It may lead to lower rates of unsafe abortion with a lower need for physicians and resources.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/abortion-in-africa] In Sub-Saharan Africa, an average of 1.7 million women per year receive post-abortion care (PAC).
[src:indian-ocean-trade/abortion-in-africa] National average annual rates range from 4–7 per 1,000 women in Nigeria to about 15 per 1,000 women in Uganda.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/abortion-in-africa] PAC patients may be treated as inpatients or outpatients depending on the severity of their cases and national guidelines.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/abortion-in-africa] PAC is provided by varied professionals at public and private providers.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/abortion-in-africa] In some countries, nurses and clinical officers have been shown to treat abortion as well as physicians.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/abortion-in-africa] PAC services are concentrated in urban facilities owned by the government or NGOs and referral hospitals.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/abortion-in-africa] In countries where abortion is illegal, many patients have their abortions recorded as miscarriages.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/abortion-in-africa] About 44% of abortions require care for complications or incompleteness.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/abortion-in-africa] Of women who require treatment, 43% do not receive it.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/abortion-in-africa] These rates are highest among poor rural women and lowest among non-poor urban women.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/abortion-in-africa] Severe complications are more likely to occur in later stages of pregnancy.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/abortion-in-africa] In Southern Africa, where abortion is widely legal, there are fewer cases of treatment of abortion complications.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/abortion-in-africa] Young and unmarried women comprise large proportions of PAC patients in Sub-Saharan Africa.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/abortion-in-africa] PAC patients comprise large proportions of adolescents receiving gynecological care.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/abortion-in-africa] Delayed or deficient PAC is a major factor in abortion mortality.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/abortion-in-africa] Many women delay PAC because they expect the problem to be go away, lack the money or transportation, or fear social consequences or arrest.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/abortion-in-africa] Most arrests for abortion are initiated by healthcare providers.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/abortion-in-africa] Some PAC providers refuse care or demand bribes.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/abortion-in-africa] Delays occur after women seek treatment, as local health centers lack the training or equipment and must make referrals to higher-level facilities.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/abortion-in-africa] Patients in rural areas face delays since services are more available in cities.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/abortion-in-africa] Many providers lack adequate training in PAC methods, violate standards, and perform unsafe procedures.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/abortion-in-africa] Some national abortion laws are unclear about PAC.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/abortion-in-africa] WHO standards recommend manual vacuum aspiration (MVA) or misoprostol for PAC.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/abortion-in-africa] Use of misoprostol leads to higher safety, as misoprostol can be easily purchased, stored, and used, and it can be stocked in primary care facilities.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/abortion-in-africa] Many places continue to use dilation and curettage (D&C), a surgical method not recommended by WHO.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/abortion-in-africa] Sublingual administration of misoprostol is effective and accepted in many African countries.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/abortion-in-africa] Post-abortion family planning services effectively inform patients of options such as long-acting reversible contraceptives.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/abortion-in-africa] These services increase the use of effective contraception.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/abortion-in-africa] The most common contraceptives offered are injectables, oral contraceptive pills, condoms, and intrauterine devices.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/abortion-in-africa] Many PAC providers do not offer family planning services.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/abortion-in-africa] The annual spending on PAC in Sub-Saharan Africa is $228 million, as of 2019.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/abortion-in-africa] Costs to national health systems vary based on population, unsafe abortion rate, and provisions for care in primary and secondary facilities.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/abortion-in-africa] Less expensive abortions result in more expensive PAC.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/abortion-in-africa] The costs to the healthcare systems of PAC are greater than the costs of safe abortion.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/abortion-in-africa] Stigma about abortion and unawareness of PAC among medical workers contribute to low availability.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/abortion-in-africa] As of 2018, PAC is offered by fewer than 10% of primary care facilities in Kenya, Namibia, Rwanda, Tanzania and Uganda.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/abortion-in-africa] Training and intervention programs are effective in expanding access, reducing delays, and improving midwives' and nurses' willingness and ability to provide PAC.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/abortion-in-africa] Rollout of misoprostol, community health education, and community partnerships have been shown to increase access to PAC in many countries.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/abortion-in-africa] PAC is less available in countries where abortion is illegal.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/abortion-in-africa] Scholars have criticized metrics of PAC use for overlooking the harm caused by illegal abortion.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/abortion-in-africa] The table below summarises the legal grounds for abortion in all African Member states of the United Nations.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/abortion-in-africa] This table is mostly based on data compiled by the United Nations up to 2019, with some updates, additions and clarifications citing other sources.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/abortion-in-africa] The table below summarises the legal grounds for abortion in African states with limited recognition.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/abortion-in-africa] The table below summarizes the legal grounds for abortion in African dependent territories of countries outside of Africa.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/afghan-turkestan] The whole territory of Afghan Turkestan, from the junction of the Kokcha river with the Amu Darya on the north-east to the province of Herat on the south-west, was some 800 kilometres (500 mi) in length, with an average width from the Russian frontier to the Hindu Kush of 183 km (114 mi).
[src:indian-ocean-trade/afghan-turkestan] It thus comprised about 147,000 km2 (57,000 sq mi) or roughly two-ninths of the former Kingdom of Afghanistan.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/afghan-turkestan] The area is agriculturally poor except in the river valleys, being rough and mountainous towards the south, but subsiding into undulating wastes and pasture-lands towards the Karakum Desert.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/afghan-turkestan] The province included the khanates of Kunduz, Tashkurgan, Balkh, and Akcha in the east and the four khanates or *Chahar Wilayat* ("four domains") of Saripul, Shibarghan, Andkhoy (city), and Maymana in the west.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/afghan-turkestan] The bulk of the people are Uzbeks and Turkmens with large concentrations of Hazaras, Qizilbashs, Tatars, Tajiks, and Pashtuns.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/afghan-turkestan] Ancient Balkh or Bactria was an integral part of Bactria–Margiana Archaeological Complex, and was occupied by Indo-Iranians.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/afghan-turkestan] In the 5th century BCE, it became a province of the Achaemenian Empire and later became part of the Seleucid Empire.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/afghan-turkestan] About 250 BC Diodotus (Theodotus), governor of Bactria under the Seleucidae, declared his independence, and commenced the history of the Greco-Bactrian dynasties, which succumbed to Parthian and nomadic movements about 126 BC.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/afghan-turkestan] After this came a Buddhist era which has left its traces in the gigantic sculptures at Bamian and the rock-cut topes of Haibak.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/afghan-turkestan] The district was devastated by Genghis Khan, and has never since fully recovered its prosperity.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/afghan-turkestan] For about a century it belonged to the Delhi empire, and then fell into Uzbek hands.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/afghan-turkestan] In the 18th century it formed part of the dominion of Ahmad Shah Durrani, and so remained under his son Timur Shah.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/afghan-turkestan] But under the fratricidal wars of Timur's sons the separate khanates fell back under the independent rule of various Uzbek chiefs.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/afghan-turkestan] At the beginning of the 19th century they belonged to Bukhara; but under the emir Dost Mohammad, the Afghans recovered Balkh and Tashkurgan in 1850, Akcha and the four western khanates in 1855, and Kunduz in 1859.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/afghan-turkestan] Dost Mohammad's earliest campaigns begin in the 1830s in the Afghan Turkestan Campaign of 1838-39.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/afghan-turkestan] The sovereignty over Andkhoy, Shibarghan, Saripul, and Maymana was in dispute between Bukhara and Kabul until settled by the Anglo-Russian agreement of 1873 in favour of the Afghan claim.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/afghan-turkestan] Under the strong rule of Abdur Rahman these outlying territories were closely welded to Kabul; but after the accession of Habibullah the bonds once more relaxed.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/afghan-turkestan] In the late 19th and 20th centuries, many ethnic Pashtuns either voluntarily or involuntarily settled in Afghan Turkestan.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/afghan-turkestan] In 1890, the district of Qataghan and Badakhshan was divided from Afghan Turkestan and made into the Qataghan-Badakhshan Province.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/afghan-turkestan] Administration of the province was assigned to the Northern Bureau in Kabul.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/amr-ibn-al-as] Amr launched the expedition that conquered Egypt on his own initiative in late 639, defeating the Byzantines in a string of victories ending with the surrender of Alexandria in 641 or 642.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/amr-ibn-al-as] It was the swiftest of the early Muslim conquests.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/amr-ibn-al-as] This was followed by westward advances by Amr as far as Tripoli in present-day Libya.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/amr-ibn-al-as] In a treaty signed with the Byzantine governor Cyrus, Amr guaranteed the security of Egypt's population and imposed a poll tax on non-Muslim adult men.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/amr-ibn-al-as] He maintained the Coptic-dominated bureaucracy and cordial ties with the Coptic patriarch Benjamin.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/amr-ibn-al-as] He founded Fustat as the provincial capital with the mosque later called after him at its center.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/amr-ibn-al-as] Amr ruled relatively independently, acquired significant wealth, and upheld the interests of the Arab conquerors who formed Fustat's garrison in relation to the central authorities in Medina.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/amr-ibn-al-as] After gradually diluting Amr's authority, Caliph Uthman (r.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/amr-ibn-al-as] 644–656) dismissed him in 646 after accusations of incompetence from his successor Abd Allah ibn Sa'd.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/amr-ibn-al-as] After mutineers from Egypt assassinated Uthman, Amr distanced himself from their cause, despite previously instigating opposition against Uthman.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/amr-ibn-al-as] In the ensuing First Fitna, Amr joined Mu'awiya ibn Abi Sufyan against Caliph Ali (r.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/amr-ibn-al-as] 656–661) due to promises of the governorship of Egypt and its tax revenues.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/amr-ibn-al-as] Amr served as Mu'awiya's representative in the abortive arbitration talks to end the war.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/amr-ibn-al-as] Afterward, he wrested control of Egypt from Ali's loyalists, killing its governor Muhammad ibn Abi Bakr, and assumed the governorship instead.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/amr-ibn-al-as] Mu'awiya kept him in his post after establishing the Umayyad Caliphate in 661 and Amr ruled the province until his death.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/amr-ibn-al-as] His father, al-As ibn Wa'il, was a wealthy landowner from the Banu Sahm clan of the Quraysh tribe of Mecca.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/amr-ibn-al-as] 622, Amr inherited from him the lucrative al-Waht estate and vineyards near Ta'if.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/amr-ibn-al-as] Amr's mother was al-Nabigha bint Harmala from the Banu Jallan clan of the Anaza tribe.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/amr-ibn-al-as] She had been taken captive and sold, in succession, to several members of the Quraysh, one of whom was Amr's father.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/amr-ibn-al-as] As such, Amr had two maternal half-brothers, Amr ibn Atatha of the Banu Adi and Uqba ibn Nafi of the Banu Fihr, and a half-sister from the Banu Abd Shams.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/amr-ibn-al-as] Amr is physically described in the traditional sources as being short with broad shoulders, having a large head with a wide forehead and wide mouth, long arms and a long beard.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/amr-ibn-al-as] There are conflicting reports about when Amr embraced Islam, with the most credible version placing it in 629/630, not long before the conquest of Mecca by Muhammad.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/amr-ibn-al-as] According to this account, he converted alongside the Qurayshites Khalid ibn al-Walid and Uthman ibn Talha.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/amr-ibn-al-as] According to Amr's own testimony, transmitted by his fourth-generation descendant Amr ibn Shu'ayb, he converted in Axum in the presence of King Armah (Najashi) and met Muhammad in Medina upon the latter's return from the Battle of Khaybar in 628.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/amr-ibn-al-as] Amr conditioned his conversion on the forgiveness of his past sins and an "active part in affairs", according to a report cited by the historian Ibn Asakir (d.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/amr-ibn-al-as] Indeed, in October 629, Amr was tasked by Muhammad with leading the raid on Dhat al-Salasil, likely located in the northern Hejaz (western Arabia), a lucrative opportunity for Amr in view of the potential war spoils.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/amr-ibn-al-as] The purpose of the raid is unclear, though the modern historian Fred Donner speculates that it was to "break up a gathering of hostile tribal groups" possibly backed by the Byzantine Empire.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/amr-ibn-al-as] 833) holds that Amr rallied the nomadic Arabs in the region "to make war on [Byzantine] Syria".
[src:indian-ocean-trade/amr-ibn-al-as] The tribal groups targeted in the raid included the Quda'a in general and the Bali specifically.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/amr-ibn-al-as] Amr's paternal grandmother hailed from the Bali, and this may have motivated his appointment to the command by Muhammad as Amr was instructed to recruit tribesmen from the Bali and the other Quda'a tribes of Balqayn and Banu Udhra.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/amr-ibn-al-as] Following the raid, a delegation of the Bali embraced Islam.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/amr-ibn-al-as] Amr further consecrated ties with the tribe by marrying a Bali woman, with whom he had his son Muhammad.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/amr-ibn-al-as] Muhammad appointed Amr as the governor of Oman and he remained there until being informed of Muhammad's death in 632.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/amr-ibn-al-as] Amr was personally chosen by Muhammad to deliver a letter calling the kings of Oman, the Julanda brothers Abd and Jayfa, to convert to Islam while being accompanied by Sa'id ibn Aws al-Ansari.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/amr-ibn-al-as] The death of Muhammad prompted several Arab tribes to defect from the nascent Medina-based Muslim polity in the Ridda wars.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/amr-ibn-al-as] Muhammad's successor Caliph Abu Bakr (r.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/amr-ibn-al-as] 632–634) appointed Amr to rein in the apostate Quda'a tribes, and among those targeted were the Hejazi branches of the Bali.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/amr-ibn-al-as] Amr's campaigns, which were supported by the commander Shurahbil ibn Hasana, succeeded in restoring Medina's authority as far as the northern frontier with Syria.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/amr-ibn-al-as] Amr was one of four commanders dispatched by Abu Bakr to conquer Syria in 633.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/amr-ibn-al-as] The focus of Amr's campaign was Palestine, to which he had been appointed governor by Abu Bakr before his departure.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/amr-ibn-al-as] As a Qurayshite merchant Amr was likely already well-acquainted with the routes to Gaza, a principle terminal for Meccan caravans.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/amr-ibn-al-as] He took the coastal route of the Hejaz, reaching Ayla, a Muslim possession since 630, before breaking west into the Negev desert or possibly the Sinai.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/amr-ibn-al-as] He arrived near the villages of Dathin and Badan in Gaza's environs where he entered into talks with Gaza's Byzantine commander.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/amr-ibn-al-as] After the negotiations broke down, Amr's men bested the Byzantines at the Battle of Dathin on 4 February 634 and set up headquarters at Ghamr al-Arabat in the middle of the Wadi Araba.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/amr-ibn-al-as] Most accounts hold that Amr's army was 3,000-strong; the Muhajirun (emigrants from Mecca to Medina) and the Ansar (natives of Medina), who together formed the core of the earliest Muslim converts, dominated his forces according to al-Waqidi (d.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/amr-ibn-al-as] 823), while the 9th-century historian Ibn A'tham holds that Amr's army consisted of 3,300 Qurayshite and allied horsemen, 1,700 horsemen from the Banu Sulaym and 200 from the Yemenite tribe of Madh'hij.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/amr-ibn-al-as] The historian Philip Mayerson considers the troop figures to be "unquestionably exaggerated" but still representing the largest Arab fighting force to have ever been assembled in southern Palestine and the Sinai until then.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/amr-ibn-al-as] Amr conquered the area around Gaza by February or March 634 and proceeded to besiege Caesarea, the capital of Byzantine Palestine, in July.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/amr-ibn-al-as] He soon after abandoned the siege upon the approach of a large Byzantine army.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/amr-ibn-al-as] Amr occupied numerous towns in Palestine, including Bayt Jibrin, Yibna, Amwas, Lydda, Jaffa, Nablus and Sebastia.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/amr-ibn-al-as] Most of these localities surrendered after little resistance due to the flight of Byzantine troops; consequently, there is scant information about them in the traditional accounts of the conquest.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/amr-ibn-al-as] 634–644) appointed or confirmed Amr as the commander and governor of the military district of Palestine.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/amr-ibn-al-as] The Muslims pursued the Byzantine army northward and besieged them at Pella for four months.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/amr-ibn-al-as] Amr may have retained overall command of the Muslim armies until this point, though other accounts assign command to Khalid or Abu Ubayda ibn al-Jarrah.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/amr-ibn-al-as] In any case, the Muslims landed a heavy blow against the Byzantines in the ensuing Battle of Fahl in December 634 or January 635.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/amr-ibn-al-as] Afterward, Amr and Shurahbil may have been sent to besiege Beisan, which capitulated after minor resistance.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/amr-ibn-al-as] The Muslims proceeded to besiege Damascus, where the remnants of the Byzantine army from the battles of Ajnadayn and Fahl had gathered.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/amr-ibn-al-as] Amr was positioned at the Bab Tuma gate, the Muslim commanders having each been assigned to block one of the city's entrances.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/amr-ibn-al-as] By August–September 635, Damascus surrendered to the Muslims.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/amr-ibn-al-as] In response to the series of defeats, the Byzantine emperor Heraclius (r.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/amr-ibn-al-as] Following Yarmouk, the Muslims attempted to capture Jerusalem, where Amr had previously sent an advance force.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/amr-ibn-al-as] Abu Ubayda led the siege of Jerusalem, in which Amr participated, but the city only surrendered after Caliph Umar arrived in person to conclude a treaty with its defenders.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/amr-ibn-al-as] Amr was one of the witnesses of the Treaty of Umar.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/amr-ibn-al-as] From Jerusalem, Amr then proceeded to besiege and capture the city of Gaza.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/amr-ibn-al-as] From his base in southern Palestine, Amr launched the conquest of Byzantine Egypt.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/amr-ibn-al-as] He had established trading interests there before his conversion to Islam, making him aware of its importance in international trade.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/amr-ibn-al-as] The traditional Muslim sources generally hold that Amr undertook the campaign with Caliph Umar's reluctant approval, though a number of accounts hold that he entered the region without Umar's authorization.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/amr-ibn-al-as] At the head of 4,000 cavalries and with no siege engines, Amr arrived at the frontier town of al-Arish along the northern Sinai coastline on 12 December 639.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/amr-ibn-al-as] He captured the strategic Mediterranean port city of Pelusium (al-Farama) following a month-long siege and moved against Bilbeis, which also fell after a month-long siege.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/amr-ibn-al-as] Amr halted his campaign before the fortified Byzantine stronghold of Babylon, at the head of the Nile Delta, and requested reinforcements from Umar.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/amr-ibn-al-as] The latter dispatched al-Zubayr ibn al-Awwam, a leading Qurayshite companion of Muhammad, with a 4,000-strong force, which joined Amr's camp in June 640.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/amr-ibn-al-as] Amr retained the supreme command of Arab forces in Egypt.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/amr-ibn-al-as] In the following month, his army decisively defeated the Byzantines at the Battle of Heliopolis.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/amr-ibn-al-as] He captured Memphis soon after and besieged Babylon.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/amr-ibn-al-as] During the siege, Amr entered truce negotiations with the Alexandria-based Byzantine governor Cyrus; Emperor Heraclius opposed the talks and recalled Cyrus to Constantinople.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/amr-ibn-al-as] Though strong resistance was put up by Babylon's defenders, their morale was sapped after news of Heraclius' death in February 641.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/amr-ibn-al-as] Amr made an agreement with the Byzantine garrison, allowing their peaceful withdrawal toward the provincial capital Alexandria on 9 April 641.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/amr-ibn-al-as] Amr then sent his lieutenants to conquer different parts of the country.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/amr-ibn-al-as] One of them, Kharija ibn Hudhafa, captured the Fayyum oasis, Oxyrhynchus (Bahnasa), Hermopolis (el-Ashmunein) and Akhmim, all in Middle Egypt, and an unspecified number of villages in Upper Egypt.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/amr-ibn-al-as] It fell virtually without resistance after Cyrus, who had since been restored to office, and Amr finalized a treaty in Babylon guaranteeing the security of Egypt's inhabitants and imposing a poll tax on adult males.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/amr-ibn-al-as] The date of the city's surrender was likely November 642.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/amr-ibn-al-as] Taking advantage of the uncertain political situation in the wake of Umar's death in 644 and the meager Arab military presence in Alexandria, Emperor Constans II (r.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/amr-ibn-al-as] 641–668) dispatched a naval expedition led by a certain Manuel which occupied the city and killed most of its Arab garrison in 645.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/amr-ibn-al-as] Alexandria's elite and most of the inhabitants assisted the Byzantines; medieval Byzantine, Coptic and, to a lesser extent, Muslim sources indicate the city was not firmly in Arab hands during the preceding three years.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/amr-ibn-al-as] Byzantine forces pushed deeper into the Nile Delta, but Amr forced them back at the Battle of Nikiou.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/amr-ibn-al-as] He besieged and captured Alexandria in the summer of 646; most of the Byzantines, including Manuel, were slain, many of its inhabitants were killed and the city was burned until Amr ordered an end to the onslaught.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/amr-ibn-al-as] Afterward, Muslim rule in Alexandria was gradually solidified.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/amr-ibn-al-as] In contrast to the disarray of the Byzantine defense, the Muslim forces under Amr's command were unified and organized; Amr frequently coordinated with Caliph Umar and his own troops for all major military decisions.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/amr-ibn-al-as] In the absence of siege engines, Amr oversaw long sieges of heavily fortified Byzantine positions, most prominently Babylon, cut supply lines and engaged in long wars of attrition.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/amr-ibn-al-as] He made advantageous use out of the nomads in his ranks, who were seasoned in hit-and-run tactics, and his settled troops, who were generally more acquainted with siege warfare.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/amr-ibn-al-as] His cavalry-dominated army moved through Egypt's deserts and oases with relative ease.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/amr-ibn-al-as] After the surrender of Alexandria in 642, Amr marched his army westward, bypassing the fortified Byzantine coastal strongholds of Paraetonium (Marsa Matruh), Appolonia Sozusa (Marsa Soussa) and Ptolemais (Tolmeita), capturing Barca and reaching Torca in Cyrenaica.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/amr-ibn-al-as] Toward the end of the year, Amr launched a second cavalry assault targeting Tripoli.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/amr-ibn-al-as] The city was heavily fortified by the Byzantines and contained several naval vessels in its harbor.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/amr-ibn-al-as] Due to his lack of siege engines, he employed the lengthy siege tactic used in the Egyptian conquest.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/amr-ibn-al-as] After about a month, his troops entered Tripoli through a vulnerable point in its walls and sacked the city.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/amr-ibn-al-as] Its fall, which entailed the evacuation by sea of the Byzantine garrison and most of the population, is dated to 642 or 643/44.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/amr-ibn-al-as] Though the Arab hold over Cyrenaica and Zawila to the far south remained firm for decades except for a short-lived Byzantine occupation in 690, Tripoli was recaptured by the Byzantines a few years after Amr's entry.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/amr-ibn-al-as] The region was definitively conquered by the Arabs during the reign of Caliph Abd al-Malik (r.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/amr-ibn-al-as] The mosque was originally founded by Amr in 641 but was redesigned and expanded significantly over the next several centuries.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/amr-ibn-al-as] Amr "regulated the government of the country [Egypt], administration of justice and the imposition of taxes", according to the historian A.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/amr-ibn-al-as] During his siege of Babylon, Amr had erected an encampment near the fortress.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/amr-ibn-al-as] He originally intended for Alexandria to serve as the Arabs' capital in Egypt, but Umar rejected this on the basis that no body of water, i.e. the Nile, should separate the caliph from his army.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/amr-ibn-al-as] Instead, following Alexandria's surrender, in 641 or 642, Amr made his encampment near Babylon the permanent garrison town (*miṣr*) of Fustat, the first town founded by the Arabs in Egypt.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/amr-ibn-al-as] Its location along the eastern bank of the Nile River and at the head of the Nile Delta and edge of the Eastern Desert strategically positioned it to dominate the Upper and Lower halves of Egypt.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/amr-ibn-al-as] Fustat's proximity to Babylon, where Amr also established an Arab garrison, afforded the Arab settlers a convenient means to employ and oversee the Coptic bureaucratic officials who inhabited Babylon and proved critical to running the day-to-day affairs of the Arab government.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/amr-ibn-al-as] Amr had the original tents of Fustat replaced with mud brick and baked brick dwellings.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/amr-ibn-al-as] Documents found in Hermopolis (al-Ashmunayn) dating from the 640s confirm official orders to forward building materials to Babylon to construct the new city.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/amr-ibn-al-as] The city was organized into allotments over an area stretching 5–6 kilometers (3.1–3.7 mi) along the Nile and 1–2 kilometers (0.62–1.24 mi) inland to the east.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/amr-ibn-al-as] The allotments were distributed among the components of Amr's army, with priority given to the Quraysh, the Ansar and Amr's personal guard, the 'Ahl al-Rāya' (People of the Banner), which included several Bali tribesmen as a result of their kinship and marital ties to Amr.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/amr-ibn-al-as] An opposing theory holds that Amr did not assign the plots; rather, the tribes staked their own claims and Amr established a commission to resolve the ensuing land disputes.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/amr-ibn-al-as] At the center of the new capital Amr built a congregational mosque, later known as the Amr ibn al-As Mosque; the original structure was frequently redesigned and expanded between its foundation and its final form in 827.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/amr-ibn-al-as] Amr had his own dwelling built immediately east of the mosque and it most likely served as his government headquarters.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/amr-ibn-al-as] In the northwestern part of Alexandria, Amr built a hilltop congregational mosque, later called after him, before the Byzantine occupation of 645/46, after which he built a second called the Mosque of Mercy; neither mosque has been presently identified.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/amr-ibn-al-as] Adjacent to the congregational mosque, Amr took personal ownership of a fort, which he later donated for government use.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/amr-ibn-al-as] This part of the city became the administrative and social core of Arab settlement in Alexandria.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/amr-ibn-al-as] Accounts vary as to the number of troops Amr garrisoned in the city, ranging from 1,000 soldiers from the Azd and Banu Fahm tribes to a quarter of the army which was replaced on a rotational basis every six months.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/amr-ibn-al-as] As per the 641 treaty with Cyrus, Amr imposed a poll tax of two gold dinars on non-Muslim adult males.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/amr-ibn-al-as] He imposed other measures, sanctioned by Umar, that entailed the inhabitants' regular provision of wheat, honey, oil and vinegar as a subsistence allowance for the Arab troops.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/amr-ibn-al-as] He had these goods stored in a distribution warehouse called *dār al-rizq*.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/amr-ibn-al-as] After taking a census of the Muslims, he further ordered that each Muslim be annually supplied by the inhabitants a highly embroidered wool robe (Egyptian robes were prized by the Arabs), a burnous, a turban, a sirwal (trousers) and shoes.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/amr-ibn-al-as] In a Greek papyrus dated to 8 January 643 and containing Amr's seal (a fighting bull), Amr (transliterated as "Ambros") requests fodder for his army's animals and bread for his soldiers from an Egyptian village.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/amr-ibn-al-as] According to the historian Martin Hinds, there is "no evidence" that Amr "did anything to streamline the cumbersome fiscal system taken over from the Byzantines; rather, the upheavals of conquest can only have made the system more open to abuse than ever".
[src:indian-ocean-trade/amr-ibn-al-as] After entering Alexandria, Amr invited the Coptic patriarch Benjamin to return to the city after his years of exile under Cyrus.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/amr-ibn-al-as] The patriarch maintained close ties with Amr and restored the monasteries of Wadi al-Natrun, including the Saint Macarius Monastery, which functions until the present-day.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/amr-ibn-al-as] Kennedy, "Benjamin played a major role in the survival of the Coptic Church through the transition to Arab rule".
[src:indian-ocean-trade/amr-ibn-al-as] Amr acted relatively independent as governor and retained much of the surplus tax revenue of the province for the benefit of its troops despite pressure from Umar to forward proceeds to Medina.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/amr-ibn-al-as] He also amassed significant personal wealth in Egypt, part of which was confiscated by Muhammad ibn Maslama on Umar's orders.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/amr-ibn-al-as] At a certain point, the Caliph separated Upper Egypt from Amr's administration and appointed Abd Allah ibn Sa'd over the region.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/amr-ibn-al-as] 644–656) initially kept Amr in his governorship and forged marital links with him by wedding to him his maternal half-sister Umm Kulthum bint Uqba ibn Abi Mu'ayt.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/amr-ibn-al-as] Uthman diluted Amr's power in 645/46 by transferring fiscal responsibilities to Ibn Abi Sarh, his own relative, leaving Amr in charge of military affairs.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/amr-ibn-al-as] Amr and Ibn Sa'd lodged complaints to Uthman each alleging the other of incompetence, prompting Uthman to dismiss Amr entirely and replace him in his duties with Ibn Sa'd.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/amr-ibn-al-as] Uthman's appointee established an effective fiscal system that largely preserved its Byzantine predecessor.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/amr-ibn-al-as] Ibn Sa'd reduced the fiscal privileges of Egypt's original Arab military settlers, who had been shown favor by Amr, and secured the remittance of the surplus to Medina.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/amr-ibn-al-as] This led to the consternation of the Arab garrisons and the native officials and elite, all of whom were "deprived of the opportunities for self-enrichment which they had hitherto enjoyed", according to Hinds.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/amr-ibn-al-as] Open opposition to Ibn Sa'd and Uthman began under the leadership of the Qurayshite Muhammad ibn Abi Hudhayfa in 654/55.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/amr-ibn-al-as] Upon his return to Medina, Amr openly criticized Uthman.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/amr-ibn-al-as] The caliph and Amr engaged in a number of heated public exchanges and, according to a report in the Islamic traditional sources, Amr incited Muhammad's senior companions Ali, al-Zubayr and Talha ibn Ubayd Allah, as well as the Hajj pilgrims in Mecca, against Uthman.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/amr-ibn-al-as] He lobbied Muhammad's wife A'isha for support and the latter pressed Uthman to reappoint Amr to Egypt citing its garrisons' satisfaction with his rule.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/amr-ibn-al-as] In a sermon at the mosque in Medina in June 656 and a letter penned to the Muslim leaders in Syria, Uthman mentioned that he had intended to reappoint Amr but did not follow through as a result of the latter's excessive insult.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/amr-ibn-al-as] After his last exchange with Uthman, Amr retired to his estate in southern Palestine.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/amr-ibn-al-as] 1226) also suggest that Ajlan was located in the area of Bayt Jibrin.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/amr-ibn-al-as] Amr had likely become owner of the estate through a caliphal grant, though he possibly could have taken possession of it in the course of his conquest of Palestine and his ownership had been confirmed by the caliphs.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/amr-ibn-al-as] He lived on the estate, where he derived agricultural revenue, with his sons Muhammad and Abd Allah.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/amr-ibn-al-as] At his estate Amr received news of the siege of Uthman's house and the caliph's subsequent assassination by Amr's Egyptian partisans.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/amr-ibn-al-as] The roughly 400–600 Egyptian mutineers had protested Uthman's fiscal centralization policies in Medina and accused him of favoring his relatives over the early Muslim converts.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/amr-ibn-al-as] The caliph had initially persuaded them to withdraw, but when they intercepted a letter on their departure ordering Ibn Abi Sarh to punish them, they turned back and assaulted Uthman in his home.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/amr-ibn-al-as] In an anecdote cited by al-Baladhuri, Amr is quoted as taking partial credit for Uthman's assassination.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/amr-ibn-al-as] Ali succeeded Uthman, but did not reappoint Amr to his post in Egypt.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/amr-ibn-al-as] Amr was one of a number of figures held culpable for Uthman's death by the slain caliph's clan, the Banu Umayya (Umayyads), most prominently by Uthman's uterine brother and Amr's former brother-in-law al-Walid ibn Uqba.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/amr-ibn-al-as] Nonetheless the governor of Syria, which included Palestine, the Umayyad Mu'awiya ibn Abi Sufyan, had left Amr on his estate undisturbed.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/amr-ibn-al-as] As pressure from the Umayyads increased against him, Amr distanced himself from any role in Uthman's death and wrote Mu'awiya to execute or banish the participating Egyptian troops who had been apprehended as they passed through Mu'awiya's jurisdiction on their way back to Egypt.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/amr-ibn-al-as] After Ali's victory against al-Zubayr, Talha and Aisha at the Battle of the Camel in Iraq, Mu'awiya, who maintained his opposition to Ali, became the focus of the Caliph's attention.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/amr-ibn-al-as] Mu'awiya summoned Amr to discuss an alliance against Ali.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/amr-ibn-al-as] In the ensuing negotiations, Amr pressed Mu'awiya for lifetime possession of Egypt, to which Mu'awiya ultimately acceded after being persuaded by his brother Utba ibn Abi Sufyan.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/amr-ibn-al-as] The public agreement, composed by Amr's *mawlā* Wardan and made in Jerusalem, secured Amr's allegiance to Mu'awiya in return for the latter's assistance in gaining control of Egypt from Ali's governor.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/amr-ibn-al-as] To secure the defense of his Syrian realm from Ali's loyalists in Egypt, Amr counseled Mu'awiya to secure the support of the Judhamite chief in Palestine, Natil ibn Qays, by ignoring his seizure of the district treasury; Natil subsequently joined Mu'awiya's cause.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/amr-ibn-al-as] Amr then advised Mu'awiya to lead the Syrian army in person against Ali, who began his march toward Syria in late May 657.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/amr-ibn-al-as] When Ali's Iraqi forces set up camp around Siffin, south of the Euphrates town of Raqqa, in early June, Mu'awiya's advance guard led by Abu al-A'war refused them access to the watering places under their control.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/amr-ibn-al-as] After Ali protested, Amr advised Mu'awiya to accept their request as preventing access to water might rally the hitherto demotivated Iraqis to a determined fight against the Syrians.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/amr-ibn-al-as] Mu'awiya refused and the Iraqis subsequently defeated the Syrians led by Amr and Abu al-A'war in a skirmish known as the "Day of the Euphrates".
[src:indian-ocean-trade/amr-ibn-al-as] As the leader of the Syrian cavalry, Amr held the overall field command for Mu'awiya's forces in the ensuing weeks-long Battle of Siffin and on occasion personally participated in direct combat, though without particular distinction.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/amr-ibn-al-as] At one point in the battle, he raised a black fabric given to him by Muhammad at the tip of his spear, symbolizing the command role given to him by Muhammad.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/amr-ibn-al-as] As the Iraqis gained the battlefield advantage, Amr proposed to Mu'awiya that their men tie leaves from the Qur'an at the tips of their lances in an appeal to Ali's men to settle the conflict peacefully.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/amr-ibn-al-as] It served as a successful ruse which ended the fighting as the battle turned in Ali's favor and sowed uncertainty in Ali's ranks.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/amr-ibn-al-as] The Caliph heeded the majority will in his army to settle the matter diplomatically; an arbitration was agreed with Amr representing Mu'awiya and Abu Musa al-Ash'ari representing Ali.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/amr-ibn-al-as] Amr met with Ali once and the two exchanged insults, but Ali ultimately agreed to Amr's condition that he omit his caliphal title, *amir al-mu'minin* (commander of the faithful), from the preliminary arbitration document drafted on 2 August.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/amr-ibn-al-as] The omission effectively placed Ali and Mu'awiya on an equal political footing and thereby weakened Ali's leadership position over the Muslim polity.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/amr-ibn-al-as] Amr and Abu Musa likely met twice, at Dumat al-Jandal and then Adhruh, to forge an agreement.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/amr-ibn-al-as] At Dumat al-Jandal, Amr succeeded in gaining Abu Musa's recognition that Uthman was wrongfully killed, a verdict opposed by Ali and which strengthened Syrian support for Mu'awiya, who had taken up the cause of revenge for the death of his kinsman Uthman.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/amr-ibn-al-as] At the last meeting in Adhruh, the office of the caliphate was discussed, but the meeting ended in violence and without agreement; during the brawl, Amr was physically assaulted by a Kufan partisan of Ali, but the latter was fended off by one of Amr's sons.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/amr-ibn-al-as] Abu Musa retired to Mecca, while Amr and the Syrians returned to Mu'awiya and recognized him as **amir al-mu'minin** before formally pledging allegiance to him in April/May 658.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/amr-ibn-al-as] As a result, Amr was among those invoked in a ritual curse issued by Ali during the morning prayers and became the subject of derision among the Kufan core of Ali's supporters.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/amr-ibn-al-as] As early as 656/57, Amr and Mu'awiya persuaded Ibn Abi Hudhayfa, who had seized control of Egypt after Uthman's assassination, to meet them in al-Arish, where they took him captive in a ruse.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/amr-ibn-al-as] Amr and Mu'awiya did not advance further than this point and Ibn Abi Hudhayfa was executed.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/amr-ibn-al-as] Ali's second governor in Egypt, Qays ibn Sa'd, was dismissed in late 657 due to concerns that he would defect to Mu'awiya and his next appointee, Malik ibn al-Harith, died in Qulzum (Suez) on his way to the province.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/amr-ibn-al-as] Malik's replacement was Muhammad ibn Abi Bakr, son of the first caliph and a foster son of Ali.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/amr-ibn-al-as] Ibn Abi Bakr burned the homes and arrested the families of pro-Uthman mutineers from the Fustat garrison led by Mu'awiya ibn Hudayj and Maslama ibn Mukhallad.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/amr-ibn-al-as] The latter two requested intervention by Mu'awiya, who dispatched Amr to Egypt with a 4,000–6,000-strong army.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/amr-ibn-al-as] Despite his thirteen-year absence from Egypt, Amr nonetheless mustered the support of Egypt's original Arab military settlers and their sons.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/amr-ibn-al-as] In July/August 658, his forces defeated Ali's troops at the Battle of al-Musannah between Heliopolis (Ain Shams) and Fustat.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/amr-ibn-al-as] Ibn Hudayj pursued and captured Ibn Abi Bakr and had him executed over the objections of Amr, who had been lobbied by Ibn Abi Bakr's brother Abd al-Rahman to spare his life.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/amr-ibn-al-as] As per his agreement with Mu'awiya, Amr was installed as governor of Egypt for life and ruled as a virtual partner rather than a subordinate of Mu'awiya, who had become caliph after Ali's assassination and his son Hasan's abdication in 661.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/amr-ibn-al-as] On 22 January of that year, Amr escaped an assassination attempt by the Kharijite Zadawayh or Amr ibn Bakr, who killed Amr's stand-in for the Friday prayers, Kharija ibn Hudhafa, mistaking the latter for Amr.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/amr-ibn-al-as] When the Kharijite was apprehended and brought before him, Amr proclaimed "You wanted me, but God wanted Kharija!" and he personally executed him.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/amr-ibn-al-as] Amr was permitted by the Caliph to retain personally the surplus revenues of the province after the payment of the troops' stipends and other government expenses.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/amr-ibn-al-as] He increased the original garrison at Fustat, numbering some 15,000 soldiers, with the Syrian troops he brought with him.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/amr-ibn-al-as] According to the historian Clive Foss "Amr ruled the country successfully, and with considerable independence and privilege, until his death".
[src:indian-ocean-trade/amr-ibn-al-as] Amr died of natural causes over the age of 79.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/amr-ibn-al-as] Accounts vary regarding the date of his death, though the most credible versions place it in 43 AH (663–664 CE).
[src:indian-ocean-trade/amr-ibn-al-as] He was buried at the foot of the Muqattam hills to the east of Fustat.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/amr-ibn-al-as] Due to the early Muslims' reticence to mark the graves of their dead, Amr's burial place has not been identified.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/amr-ibn-al-as] In a testament to the personal wealth that he accrued, at the time of his death he left seventy sacks of gold dinars.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/amr-ibn-al-as] His sons Abd Allah and Muhammad refused inheritance of the sums, which were then confiscated by Mu'awiya.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/amr-ibn-al-as] Abd Allah succeeded his father as governor for a few weeks until Mu'awiya replaced him with his own brother Utba.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/amr-ibn-al-as] The traditional Egypt-based Arabic and Coptic sources regard Amr positively.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/amr-ibn-al-as] The major source of information about the Muslim conquest of Egypt and the province's early Arab military generations, Ibn Abd al-Hakam (d.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/amr-ibn-al-as] 871), commends Amr for his leadership of the Egyptian conquest and as the upholder of the interests of Egypt's troops and their families against the central authorities in Medina and later Damascus.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/amr-ibn-al-as] The Egyptian Arab tradition holds that Amr was personally praised by Muhammad and was a man of wisdom and piety on his deathbed.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/amr-ibn-al-as] The nearly contemporary Coptic historian John of Nikiu (fl.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/amr-ibn-al-as] Though demographically Egypt remained largely non-Arab and non-Muslim for centuries after the conquest, the country has been continuously ruled by Muslims until the present day.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/amr-ibn-al-as] Amr's estates in Palestine remained in the possession of his descendants as late as the 10th or 11th centuries.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/amr-ibn-al-as] His granddaughter Umm Abd Allah bint Abd Allah married the Umayyad viceroy of Egypt Abd al-Aziz ibn Marwan (d.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/amr-ibn-al-as] 705) and gave birth to his sons Suhayl and Sahl and daughters Sahla and Umm al-Hakam.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/amr-ibn-al-as] The estates in Medina that Amr's descendants inherited from him were confiscated by the Abbasids after they took over the Caliphate from the Umayyads in 750.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/amr-ibn-al-as] The estates were restored to Amr's family after the intercession of his great-granddaughter Abida al-Hasna bint Shu'ayb ibn Abd Allah, who married the Abbasid prince al-Husayn ibn Abd Allah ibn Ubayd Allah ibn Abbas (d.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/indian-ocean-trade] The earliest long distance trade was by the sea-faring Austronesian peoples who settled in a vast swathe of coastal lands in the Indian Ocean from islands surrounding southern China such as Taiwan and Japan, to coastal areas of Maritime South East Asia, South Eastern India and Sri Lanka.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/indian-ocean-trade] These routes were later continued by South Asian, East Asian and European merchants such as the colonial trade routes of the Dutch East India Company.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/indian-ocean-trade] This trade continues into the modern era, with the region becoming a significant geopolitical asset competed for by China, India and other powers.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/indian-ocean-trade] The Indian Ocean has been described as the "cradle of globalisation".
[src:indian-ocean-trade/indian-ocean-trade] Up to half of the world's trade and two third of oil pass through the Ocean.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/indian-ocean-trade] The Middle East has also been a major actor in the history of western Indian Ocean trade, connecting Africa with the Middle East and South Asia.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/indian-ocean-trade] Gulf ports have played a continuous role in connecting Europe to South Asia since the Hellenistic and Roman period.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/indian-ocean-trade] The maritime trade network in the eastern Indian Ocean was run by the Austronesian peoples of Maritime Southeast Asia, with evidence supporting trade networks being established by at least 3000 BCE.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/indian-ocean-trade] Activity in Japan is shown in the Yayoi period (3rd century BCE) as evidenced by the discovery of Indo-Pacific beads.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/indian-ocean-trade] This trade network possibly expanded to reach as far as Africa and the Arabian Peninsula, and also resulting in the Austronesian colonization of Madagascar by the first half of the first millennium AD.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/indian-ocean-trade] Spices (mainly cinnamon and cassia) were traded with East Africa using catamaran and outrigger boats and sailing with the help of the Westerlies in the Indian Ocean that likely passed through the Maldives and the Chagos Archipelago.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/indian-ocean-trade] It continued up to historic times, later becoming the Maritime Silk Road and the European colonial trade routes East of the Suez.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/indian-ocean-trade] In modern days, the trade routes are still used between the Middle East and East Asia, through the major sea ports in Sri Lanka, Singapore and Indonesia to ship high value goods such as petroleum and Chinese wares.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/indian-ocean-trade] Chinese fleets under Zheng He crisscrossed the Indian Ocean during the early part of the 15th century.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/indian-ocean-trade] The missions were diplomatic rather than commercial, but many exchanges of gift and produces were made.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/indian-ocean-trade] During the 16th and 17th century, Japanese ships also made forays into Indian Ocean trade through the Red Seal ship system.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/indian-ocean-trade] The Satavahanas developed shipping ventures in Southeast Asia.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/indian-ocean-trade] During this period, between 7th to 13th century in Indonesian archipelago flourished the Srivijaya thalassocracy empire that rule the maritime trade network in maritime Southeast Asia and connecting India and China.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/indian-ocean-trade] There was an extensive maritime trade network operating between the Harappan and Mesopotamian civilizations as early as the middle Harappan Phase (2600-1900 BCE), with much commerce being handled by "middlemen merchants from Dilmun" (modern Bahrain and Failaka located in the Persian Gulf).
[src:indian-ocean-trade/indian-ocean-trade] Such long-distance sea trade became feasible with the development of plank-built watercraft, equipped with a single central mast supporting a sail of woven rushes or cloth.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/indian-ocean-trade] Several coastal settlements like Sotkagen-dor (astride Dasht River, north of Jiwani), Sokhta Koh (astride Shadi River, north of Pasni), and Balakot (near Sonmiani) in Pakistan along with Lothal in western India, testify to their role as Harappan trading outposts.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/indian-ocean-trade] Shallow harbours located at the estuaries of rivers opening into the sea allowed brisk maritime trade with Mesopotamian cities.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/indian-ocean-trade] Recent archaeological study has highlighted the growing corpus of evidence supporting direct maritime contacts between bronze age Egypt and India via the Red Sea.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/indian-ocean-trade] Scholars such as Gregory Possehl have also proposed maritime activities between the Indus Valley Civilization and East Africa.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/indian-ocean-trade] Trade between India and the Greek Ptolemaic Kingdom was started by Eudoxus of Cyzicus in 130 BCE.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/indian-ocean-trade] From Egypt, goods could be sent on to ports throughout the Mediterranean.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/indian-ocean-trade] The Kingdom's opening of Red Sea ports and improved knowledge of the seasonal monsoons resulted in a substantial increase in trade.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/indian-ocean-trade] The consolidation of the administration of the Mediterranean basin under the Roman Empire led to the strengthening of direct maritime trade with India and the elimination of the taxes extracted previously by the middlemen of various land-based trading routes.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/indian-ocean-trade] Trade between the Roman Empire and India peaked during the first two centuries of the Common Era, facilitated by the peace and prosperity that arose beginning with the reign of Roman Emperor Augustus (27 BCE – 14 CE) and ending with the Antonine plague.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/indian-ocean-trade] Strabo's mention of the vast increase in trade following the Roman annexation of Egypt indicates that the monsoon was known and utilized for trade in his time.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/indian-ocean-trade] The three main Roman ports involved with eastern trade were Arsinoe, Berenice and Myos Hormos.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/indian-ocean-trade] Arsinoe was one of the early trading centers but was soon overshadowed by the more easily accessible Myos Hormos and Berenice.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/indian-ocean-trade] The Ptolemaic dynasty exploited the strategic position of Alexandria to secure trade with the subcontinent.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/indian-ocean-trade] The course of trade with the east then seems to have been first through the harbor of Arsinoe, the present day Suez.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/indian-ocean-trade] The goods from the East African trade were landed at one of the three main Roman ports, Arsinoe, Berenice or Myos Hormos.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/indian-ocean-trade] The Romans repaired and cleared out the silted up canal from the Nile to harbor center of Arsinoe on the Red Sea.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/indian-ocean-trade] This was one of the many efforts the Roman administration had to undertake to divert as much of the trade to the maritime routes as possible.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/indian-ocean-trade] Arsinoe was eventually overshadowed by the rising prominence of Myos Hormos.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/indian-ocean-trade] The navigation to the northern ports, such as Arsinoe-Clysma, became difficult in comparison to Myos Hormos due to the northern winds in the Gulf of Suez.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/indian-ocean-trade] Venturing to these northern ports presented additional difficulties such as shoals, reefs and treacherous currents.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/indian-ocean-trade] Myos Hormos and Berenice appear to have been important ancient trading ports, possibly used by the Pharaonic traders of ancient Egypt and the Ptolemaic dynasty before falling into Roman control.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/indian-ocean-trade] The site of Berenice, since its discovery by Belzoni (1818), has been equated with the ruins near Ras Banas in Southern Egypt.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/indian-ocean-trade] However, the precise location of Myos Hormos is disputed with the latig Abu Sha'ar and the accounts given in classical literature and satellite images indicating a probable identification with Quseir el-Quadim at the end of a fortified road from Koptos on the Nile.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/indian-ocean-trade] The Quseir el-Quadim site has further been associated with Myos Hormos following the excavations at el-Zerqa, halfway along the route, which have revealed ostraca leading to the conclusion that the port at the end of this road may have been Myos Hormos.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/indian-ocean-trade] The regional ports of Barbaricum (modern Karachi), Sounagoura (central Bangladesh) Barygaza, Muziris in Kerala, Korkai, Kaveripattinam and Arikamedu on the southern tip of present-day India were the main centers of this trade, along with Kodumanal, an inland city.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/indian-ocean-trade] — Periplus of the Erythraean Sea (paragraph 49).
[src:indian-ocean-trade/indian-ocean-trade] Muziris is a lost port city on the southwestern coast of India which was a major center of trade in the ancient Tamil land between the Chera kingdom and the Roman Empire.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/indian-ocean-trade] Its location is generally identified with modern-day Cranganore (central Kerala).
[src:indian-ocean-trade/indian-ocean-trade] Large hoards of coins and innumerable shards of amphorae found at the town of Pattanam (near Cranganore) have elicited recent archeological interest in finding a probable location of this port city.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/indian-ocean-trade] The Periplus Maris Erythraei mentions a marketplace named Poduke (ch.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/indian-ocean-trade] Huntingford identified as possibly being Arikamedu in Tamil Nadu, a centre of early Chola trade (now part of Ariyankuppam), about 3 kilometres (1.9 mi) from the modern Pondicherry.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/indian-ocean-trade] Huntingford further notes that Roman pottery was found at Arikamedu in 1937, and archeological excavations between 1944 and 1949 showed that it was "a trading station to which goods of Roman manufacture were imported during the first half of the 1st century AD".
[src:indian-ocean-trade/indian-ocean-trade] Following the Roman-Persian Wars, the areas under the Roman Byzantine Empire were captured by Khosrow II of the Persian Sassanian Dynasty, but the Byzantine emperor Heraclius reconquered them (628).
[src:indian-ocean-trade/indian-ocean-trade] The Arabs, led by 'Amr ibn al-'As, crossed into Egypt in late 639 or early 640 CE.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/indian-ocean-trade] This advance marked the beginning of the Islamic conquest of Egypt and the fall of ports such as Alexandria, which used to secure trade with the Indian subcontinent by the Roman world since the Ptolemaic dynasty.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/indian-ocean-trade] During the Muslim period, in which the Muslims had dominated the trade across the Indian Ocean, the Gujaratis were bringing spices from the Moluccas as well as silk from China, in exchange for manufactured items such as textiles, and then selling them to the Egyptians and Arabs.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/indian-ocean-trade] Calicut was the center of Indian pepper exports to the Red Sea and Europe at this time with Egyptian and Arab traders being particularly active.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/indian-ocean-trade] Muslim missionaries and merchants began to spread Islam along the western shores of the Indian Ocean from the 8th century, if not earlier.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/indian-ocean-trade] A Swahili stone mosque dating to the 8th–15th centuries has been found in Shanga, Kenya.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/indian-ocean-trade] Trade across the Indian Ocean gradually introduced the Arabic script, and rice as a staple in Eastern Africa.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/indian-ocean-trade] Muslim merchants traded an estimated 1000 African slaves annually between 800 and 1700, a number that grew to c.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/indian-ocean-trade] Slave trade also occurred in the eastern Indian Ocean before the Dutch settled there around 1600 but the volume of this trade is unknown.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/indian-ocean-trade] The Portuguese under Vasco da Gama discovered a naval route to the Indian Ocean through the southern tip of Africa in 1497–98.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/indian-ocean-trade] Initially, the Portuguese were mainly active in Calicut, but the northern region of Gujarat was even more important for trade, and an essential intermediary in east–west trade.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/indian-ocean-trade] European slave trade in the Indian Ocean began when Portugal established Estado da Índia in the early 16th century.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/indian-ocean-trade] 200 slaves were exported from Mozambique annually and similar figures has been estimated for slaves brought from Asia to the Philippines during the Iberian Union (1580–1640).
[src:indian-ocean-trade/indian-ocean-trade] Venetian interests were directly threatened as the traditional trade patterns were eliminated and the Portuguese became able to undersell the Venetians in the spice trade in Europe.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/indian-ocean-trade] Venice broke diplomatic relations with Portugal and started to look at ways to counter its intervention in the Indian Ocean, sending an ambassador to the Egyptian court.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/indian-ocean-trade] Venice negotiated for Egyptian tariffs to be lowered to facilitate competition with the Portuguese, and suggested that "rapid and secret remedies" be taken against the Portuguese.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/indian-ocean-trade] The Mamluks sent a fleet in 1507 under Amir Husain Al-Kurdi, which would fight in the Battle of Chaul.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/indian-ocean-trade] The Ottomans tried to challenge Portugal's hegemony in the Persian Gulf region by sending an armada against the Portuguese under Ali Bey in 1581.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/indian-ocean-trade] They were supported in this endeavor by the chiefs of several local principalities and port towns such as Muscat, Gwadar, and Pasni.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/indian-ocean-trade] However, the Portuguese successfully intercepted and destroyed the Ottoman Armada.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/indian-ocean-trade] Subsequently, the Portuguese attacked Gwadar and Pasni on the Mekran Coast and sacked them in retaliation for providing aid and comfort to the enemy.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/indian-ocean-trade] During the 16th century the Portuguese had established bases in the Persian Gulf.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/indian-ocean-trade] In 1602, the Iranian army under the command of Imam-Quli Khan Undiladze managed to expel the Portuguese from Bahrain.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/indian-ocean-trade] In 1622, with the help of four English ships, Abbas retook Hormuz from the Portuguese in the capture of Ormuz.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/indian-ocean-trade] He replaced it as a trading centre with a new port, Bandar Abbas, nearby on the mainland, but it never became as successful.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/indian-ocean-trade] The establishment of the Dutch East India Company in the early 17th century lead to a quick increase in volume of the slave trade in the region; there were perhaps up to 500,000 slaves in various Dutch colonies during the 17th and 18th centuries in the Indian Ocean.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/indian-ocean-trade] For example, some 4000 African slaves were used to build the Colombo fortress in Dutch Ceylon.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/indian-ocean-trade] Bali and neighbouring islands supplied regional networks with c.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/indian-ocean-trade] Indian and Chinese slave traders supplied Dutch Indonesia with perhaps 25,000 slaves during 17th and 18th centuries.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/indian-ocean-trade] The East India Company (EIC) was established during the same period and in 1622 one of its ships carried slaves from the Coromandel Coast to Dutch East Indies.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/indian-ocean-trade] The EIC mostly traded in African slaves but also some Asian slaves purchased from Indian, Indonesian and Chinese slave traders.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/indian-ocean-trade] The French established colonies on the islands of Réunion and Mauritius in 1721; by 1735 some 7,200 slaves populated the Mascarene Islands, a number which had reached 133,000 in 1807.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/indian-ocean-trade] In all, Europeans traders deported 567,900–733,200 slaves within the Indian Ocean between 1500 and 1850, and almost that same number were deported from the Indian Ocean to the Americas during the same period.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/indian-ocean-trade] Slave trade in the Indian Ocean was, nevertheless, very limited compared to c.
[src:indian-ocean-trade/indian-ocean-trade] 12,000,000 slaves deported across the Atlantic.
